studyDesigns.name: Study Design
studyDesigns.rationale: Protocol-defined study design for investigating efficacy and safety

arms.name: Nasal Glucagon (LY900018)
arms.description: Single 3-mg dose of LY900018 administered nasally by study site personnel.

arms.name: Intramuscular Glucagon (IMG)
arms.description: Single 1-mg dose of IMG (GlucaGen) administered via intramuscular injection by study site personnel.

studyCohorts.name: Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus (T1DM)
studyCohorts.characteristic: Patients with a diagnosis of T1DM who have been on daily insulin therapy for at least 1 year.

studyCohorts.name: Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM)
studyCohorts.characteristic: Patients with a diagnosis of T2DM who have received daily insulin therapy for at least 1 year.

eligibilityCriteria.name: Current enrollment in other clinical trials
Recent participation in other clinical trials
Previous participation in this or other LY900018 studies
High total daily dose of insulin
History of severe hypoglycemia or loss of consciousness
History of epilepsy or seizure disorder

population.name: Study Population
population.description: Target population for the study as defined by eligibility criteria

objectives.name: Primary Objective
objectives.text: To demonstrate that 3 mg LY900018 is non-inferior to 1 mg IMG for the proportion of patients achieving treatment success from insulin-induced hypoglycemia using a non-inferiority margin of 10%

objectives.name: Secondary Safety and Tolerability Objective
objectives.text: To compare the safety and tolerability of 3 mg LY900018 with 1 mg IMG

objectives.name: Secondary PK Objective
objectives.text: To characterize the PK profile of 3 mg LY900018 compared to 1 mg IMG

objectives.name: Secondary PD Objective
objectives.text: To characterize the PD profile of 3 mg LY900018 compared to 1 mg IMG

endpoints.name: Primary Efficacy Endpoint
endpoints.text: The proportion of patients achieving treatment success defined as either an increase in PG to >70 mg/dL or an increase of >20 mg/dL from nadir within 30 minutes after administration of glucagon. The nadir is defined as the minimum PG value at the time of or within 10 minutes following glucagon administration.

endpoints.name: Safety and Tolerability Endpoints
endpoints.text: SAE, TEAEs (including gastrointestinal, nasal, and non-nasal AEs), vital signs

endpoints.name: PK Endpoint
endpoints.text: PK parameters include AUC, Cmax, Tmax

endpoints.name: PD Endpoint
endpoints.text: PD parameters include BGmax and Tmax

studyInterventions.name: LY900018
studyInterventions.description: Nasal glucagon (LY900018) is a powder formulation of human glucagon for the rescue treatment of hypoglycemia.

studyInterventions.name: GlucaGen
studyInterventions.description: Intramuscular glucagon (IMG) used as an active comparator.

studyInterventions.name: Human Regular Insulin
studyInterventions.description: Administered via IV infusion to induce hypoglycemia as part of the study procedure.

studyInterventions.name: IV Glucose
studyInterventions.description: Administered if a patient's plasma glucose remains too low after glucagon administration or if severe hypoglycemia symptoms occur.

activities.name: Collect Pre-existing Conditions and Adverse Events
activities.description: Collect Pre-existing Conditions and Adverse Events

activities.name: Vital Signs (Supine Blood Pressure, Pulse Rate, and Body Temperature)
activities.description: Vital Signs (Supine Blood Pressure, Pulse Rate, and Body Temperature)

activities.name: Clinical Lab Tests (Hematology, Clinical Chemistry, and Urinalysis)
activities.description: Clinical Lab Tests (Hematology, Clinical Chemistry, and Urinalysis)

activities.name: Pregnancy Test (Female patients of childbearing potential only)
activities.description: Pregnancy Test (Female patients of childbearing potential only)

notes.text: Abbreviations: CRU = clinical research unit; ECG = electrocardiogram; ED = early discontinuation; FSH = follicle-stimulating hormone; HbA1c = hemoglobin A1c; IMG =intramuscular glucagon; min = minutes; PD = pharmacodynamics; PG = plasma glucose; PK = pharmacokinetics; TE ADA = treatment-emergent antidrug antibodies.

a. Samples for immunogenicity, should be collected every 12 weeks (847 days) until the titer returns to baseline (ie, returns to within a single 2-fold dilution of the baseline titer) or until 1 year after the last dose of study treatment. A time-matched PK (glucagon) sample may be collected at the follow-up immunogenicity assessment(s) if warranted and agreed upon between both the investigator and sponsor.

Note: If multiple procedures take place at the same time point, the following order of the procedure should be used: ECG, vital signs, and venipuncture. Plasma glucose sample should be collected as close as possible of protocol-specified time point.

titles.text: A Phase 3 Study of Nasal Glucagon (LY900018) Compared to Intramuscular Glucagon for Treatment of Insulin-induced Hypoglycemia in Japanese Patients with Diabetes Mellitus

indications.name: Insulin-induced Hypoglycemia
indications.description: Insulin-induced Hypoglycemia in Japanese Patients with Diabetes Mellitus

study.name: A Phase 3 Study of Nasal Glucagon (LY900018) Compared to Intramuscular Glucagon for Treatment of Insulin-induced Hypoglycemia in Japanese Patients with Diabetes Mellitus

administrations.name: Human Regular Insulin infusion
administrations.dose: 2 mU/kg/min, adjustable up to 3 mU/kg/min for T1DM or 4 mU/kg/min for T2DM

administrations.name: IV Glucose rescue
administrations.duration: Administered if patient's bedside PG concentration remains <55 mg/dL at 30 minutes or <60 mg/dL at 45 minutes postdose, or as deemed clinically necessary.

substances.name: Glucagon
substances.description: A synthetic single-chain, 29-amino-acid polypeptide identical to human glucagon.

substances.name: Glucose
substances.description: Used as rescue therapy for insufficient response to glucagon.

narrativeContents.name: Study Governance, Regulatory and Ethical Considerations
narrativeContents.sectionTitle: Study Governance, Regulatory and Ethical Considerations

narrativeContents.name: Hepatic Monitoring Tests for Treatment-emergent Abnormality
narrativeContents.sectionTitle: Hepatic Monitoring Tests for Treatment-emergent Abnormality

procedures.name: Venipuncture
procedures.label: Blood Draw
procedures.description: Collection of venous blood for laboratory analysis, including pharmacokinetic (PK), pharmacodynamic (PD), clinical chemistry, hematology, serology, HbA1c, and genetic samples.

code.decode: Collection of venous blood by venipuncture

procedures.name: Urine Sample Collection
procedures.label: Urine Collection
procedures.description: Collection of urine for urinalysis, pregnancy testing, and drug screening.

procedures.name: Insulin Infusion
procedures.label: Insulin Infusion
procedures.description: Intravenous (IV) insulin infusion to induce hypoglycemia, stopped once bedside plasma glucose is <60 mg/dL.

procedures.name: Nasal Glucagon Administration
procedures.label: Nasal Glucagon Admin
procedures.description: Administration of 3 mg LY900018 via a single-use nasal dosing device.

procedures.name: Intramuscular Glucagon Administration
procedures.label: IM Glucagon Admin
procedures.description: Administration of 1 mg reconstituted intramuscular glucagon (IMG).

procedures.name: Bedside Plasma Glucose Monitoring
procedures.label: Bedside PG Monitoring
procedures.description: Monitoring of plasma glucose levels at the bedside during hypoglycemia induction and post-treatment.

procedures.name: Vital Signs Measurement
procedures.label: Vital Signs
procedures.description: Measurement of supine blood pressure, pulse rate, and body temperature at specified time points.

procedures.name: 12-lead Electrocardiogram
procedures.label: ECG
procedures.description: Recording of single and triplicate 12-lead ECGs at specified time points.

code.decode: Electrocardiogram, routine ECG with at least 12 leads; with interpretation and report

procedures.name: Physical Examination
procedures.label: Physical Exam
procedures.description: A medical examination of the patient.

procedures.name: Height and Weight Measurement
procedures.label: Height and Weight
procedures.description: Measurement of patient's height at screening and weight at specified visits.

procedures.name: Nasal Inspection
procedures.label: Nasal Inspection
procedures.description: Visual inspection of the nasal passages.

procedures.name: Injection-Site Assessment
procedures.label: Injection Site Assessment
procedures.description: Assessment of the injection site for patients receiving intramuscular glucagon (IMG).

procedures.name: Edinburgh Hypoglycemia Scale
procedures.label: Hypoglycemia Scale
procedures.description: Administration of a questionnaire to evaluate the recovery from clinical symptoms of hypoglycemia.

procedures.name: Laboratory Testing
procedures.label: Lab Tests
procedures.description: Includes clinical serology, hematology, clinical chemistry, urinalysis, HbA1c, pregnancy test, FSH, and ethanol testing.

procedures.name: Intravenous Glucose Administration
procedures.label: IV Glucose
procedures.description: Administration of IV glucose if the patient experiences signs and symptoms of severe hypoglycemia and is gauged to require intervention.

medicalDevices.name: Nasal Dosing Device
medicalDevices.label: Nasal Glucagon Device
medicalDevices.description: A user-friendly, single-use, nasal dosing device that delivers 3 mg glucagon powder for absorption through the nasal mucosa.

medicalDevices.name: Syringe and Needle
medicalDevices.label: IM Injection Kit
medicalDevices.description: Device used for intramuscular (IM) injection of reconstituted glucagon powder.

medicalDevices.name: Continuous Subcutaneous Insulin Infusion Pump
medicalDevices.label: CSII Pump
medicalDevices.description: An insulin pump for continuous subcutaneous insulin infusion.

medicalDevices.name: Intravenous Infusion Pump
medicalDevices.label: IV Pump
medicalDevices.description: Pump used for the intravenous infusion of insulin to induce hypoglycemia.

medicalDevices.name: Bedside Glucose Meter
medicalDevices.label: Glucose Meter
medicalDevices.description: Device for monitoring bedside plasma glucose (PG) levels for safety.

medicalDevices.name: 12-lead ECG Machine
medicalDevices.label: ECG Machine
medicalDevices.description: Device used to perform single and triplicate 12-lead electrocardiograms.

conditions.name: Admission Rescheduling Condition
conditions.description: Condition for proceeding with admission to the CRU on Day 1.
conditions.text: Admission can be rescheduled if PG level is not 90 to 250 mg/dL on Day 1.

conditions.name: Hypoglycemia Induction Endpoint
conditions.description: Criteria for stopping the insulin infusion.
conditions.text: Insulin infusion is stopped once bedside PG is <60 mg/dL.

conditions.name: Safety Review Gate
conditions.description: Condition for continuing enrollment after the first cohort.
conditions.text: Safety data will be reviewed after the first 6 patients are administered LY900018 in Period 2, and the remaining patients will be dosed after confirmation of the safety.

conditions.name: TE ADA Positive Status
conditions.description: Condition for entering the additional follow-up period.
conditions.text: Patients with TE ADA at follow-up/ED will undergo additional follow-up.

conditions.name: Non-inferiority Declaration Criteria
conditions.description: Statistical condition for declaring the primary objective met.
conditions.text: Non-inferiority of LY900018 will be declared if the upper limit of the 2-sided 95% CI constructed on the difference in percentage (IMG - LY900018) is less than the NIM of 10%.

transitionRules.name: Screen to Treatment Transition
transitionRules.text: Patients who meet all eligibility criteria during the screening period will be enrolled and randomized to a treatment sequence.

transitionRules.name: Transition to Additional Follow-up
transitionRules.text: Patients with TE ADA at follow-up/ED will undergo additional follow-up.

transitionRules.name: Patient Replacement Rule
transitionRules.text: If patients discontinue from the study before completion of both periods with evaluable primary outcome for any reason, the patient may be replaced. Replacement should not occur beyond 75 patients enrolled.

transitionRules.name: Continuation of Inadvertently Enrolled Patients
transitionRules.text: If a patient who did not meet enrollment criteria was inadvertently enrolled, a discussion must occur between the Lilly CP/CRP and the investigator to determine if the patient may continue in the study.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Discontinuation due to Other Study
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Discontinuation for enrollment in any other clinical study involving an investigational product or other incompatible medical research.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Investigator Decision to Discontinue
scheduleTimelineExits.description: The investigator decides that the patient should be discontinued from the study for any reason, including an AE, SAE, or a severe hypoglycemia event.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Patient Withdrawal
scheduleTimelineExits.description: The patient, or legal representative, requests to be withdrawn from the study.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Lost to Follow-up
scheduleTimelineExits.description: A patient will be considered lost to follow-up if he or she repeatedly fails to return for scheduled visits and is unable to be contacted by the study site.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Study Discontinuation for Safety
scheduleTimelineExits.description: The study will be stopped if deemed necessary for patient safety following the review of the safety data from the first 6 patients to complete Period 2 Day 1.

scheduleTimelineExits.name: Study Completion
scheduleTimelineExits.description: Completion of all protocol-required visits, including the follow-up visit 26 to 30 days after the last study treatment.

commentAnnotations.text: Note to Regulatory Authorities: This document may contain protected personal data and/or commercially confidential information exempt from public disclosure. Eli Lilly and Company requests consultation regarding release/redaction prior to any public release. In the United States, this document is subject to Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Exemption 4 and may not be reproduced or otherwise disseminated without the written approval of Eli Lilly and Company or its subsidiaries.
Patients do not need to fast for samples at screening or follow-up. At Periods 1 and 2, samples should be collected from patients who have fasted at least 8 hours before any study procedures.
When needed to confirm postmenopausal status.
If a patient sneezes immediately after administration, document using the Nasal and Non-nasal Score Questionnaire (see Appendix 6 for a copy of the questionnaire).
If an SAE occurs after signing informed consent, but prior to receiving investigational product, AND is considered reasonably possibly related to a study procedure then it MUST be reported.

Pregnancy (maternal or paternal exposure to investigational product) does not meet the definition of an AE. However, to fulfill regulatory requirements any pregnancy should be reported following the SAE process to collect data on the outcome for both mother and fetus.

Only severe hypoglycemic episodes will be reported separately as AEs. If a hypoglycemic event meets the criteria of severe, it needs to be recorded as serious in the CRF (that is, recorded as an SAE). In the case of a hypoglycemic event (other than severe), the actual glucose value, if measured, should be recorded in the CRF, with any treatments administered, and not be recorded as an AE.
